body:
@Craigacp: This is not caused by invalid domain string. I tried another model with some random domain string and it works fine. The issue is caused by your Imputer node, which should have some input, but in your model there is no input to this node. So, the input tensor type is "undefined", which is not handled when mapping the input type to enum in ONNX and hence causes SIGSEGV.
This looks an invalid model, how did you generate the model? Did you use skl2onnx?

Ah ok. The model was generated by fuzzing a valid model as we're trying to figure out if user supplied models can take down the process (which this one does). The team doing the fuzzing was using AFL https://github.com/google/AFL to generate new models.

There is an assert statement(https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/456ba4cace5b21cbd64b579ebd48e83aa4081b76/onnx/defs/data_type_utils.cc#L172), but I guess that works only in debug mode. I'll add a check there so that it doesn't throw segmentation fault.
Sounds good. Are there other similar asserts that should be made into runtime checks?

**Describe the bug**
The attached model file takes down the runtime, in roughly the same place as #4349. This model was generated via the same fuzzing process as before.

**Urgency**
We'd like to deploy a system that accepts untrusted models without failing.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): macOS
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.4.0
- Platform: Java

**To Reproduce**
Open the attached model in a session.
[fuzz_2.onnx.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/4960989/fuzz_2.onnx.zip)

**Expected behavior**
It to throw an OrtException saying the model is invalid.
